docs.abstract: The president won’t be at the first World Series game in D.C. since 1933. But he said he would go to Sunday’s game, if there is one, though he has no plans to throw out a ball.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — All of red-shirt-wearing, baby-shark-clapping Washington will be at Nationals Park on Friday night as the nation’s capital hosts its first World Series in 86 years, or at least as much of the city as can squeeze into the stadium. headline.main: Missing From Friday’s World Series Lineup in Washington: The President

docs.lead_paragraph: CHARLOTTE, N.C. — Bob Dylan’s nasally voice singing of changing times blasted from the speakers and Democratic activists crowded the patio of a craft-beer emporium on Friday as Megan and Christopher Kubala explained why, after a lifetime of ignoring midterm elections, they had just voted to elect the first Democrat since the civil rights era to represent their North Carolina congressional district.

headline.main: In North Carolina Do-Over Vote, a Reliable Republican District Is Up for Grabs

docs.abstract: After President Trump attacked the freshman Democrat from Minnesota on Twitter, Democrats pushed back. But they are choosing their words with caution.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump tweeted an edited video portraying Representative Ilhan Omar as playing down the 9/11 attacks, it took less than three hours for Senator Bernie Sanders to rush to her defense and declare her “a leader with strength and courage.” But when a Fox News anchor described Mr. Sanders on Monday night as “a staunch supporter” of Ms. Omar, the senator balked.

headline.main: For Democrats, Ilhan Omar Is a Complicated Figure to Defend
headline.print_headline: Democrats Tread Lightly in Defending One of Their Own

docs.abstract: Five months after its territorial defeat, the Islamic State is conducting guerrilla attacks as defense officials acknowledge that the terrorist group is here to stay.
docs.snippet: Five months after its territorial defeat, the Islamic State is conducting guerrilla attacks as defense officials acknowledge that the terrorist group is here to stay.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Five months after American-backed forces ousted the Islamic State from its last shard of territory in Syria, the terrorist group is gathering new strength, conducting guerrilla attacks across Iraq and Syria, retooling its financial networks and targeting new recruits at an allied-run tent camp, American and Iraqi military and intelligence officers said.

headline.main: ISIS Is Regaining Strength in Iraq and Syria
headline.print_headline: After ‘Defeat,’  ISIS Rekindles  In Middle East
